MALARIA IN HIV-INFECTED SUBJECTS - AFRICA (02)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Malaria, chloroquine resistant - Tanzania 2000.2856
Malaria, chloroquine resistant - Kenya 19990719144906
Malaria, chloroquine resistant - Kenya (04) 19990726222547
Malaria, drug resistant - Africa: overview 19990320213735
Date 7 Jul 2000
From: Steven Meshnick <meshnick@umich.edu>

There have been several previous reports showing interactions between HIV
and malaria in Africa.
Malaria and HIV have the best documented interaction in pregnant women.
Pregnant women who are HIV-1 infected develop more frequent and higher
density peripheral and placental parasitemias than do HIV-uninfected women
(2-4). One important consequence of this is that HIV-infected women have
been found to respond poorly to the standard regimen of antenatal
sufadoxine/pyrimethamine admininitration (2 doses) and may only respond if
it is administered monthly. The effect of HIV-1 on malaria parasitemia is
more pronounced in multigravidae than in primigravidae (3,4). In studies in
Mangochi and in Chikwawa (both in Malawi) the prevalence of placental
parasitemia in primigravidae at delivery was slightly decreased by HIV. In
both studies, in contrast, the prevalence of placental parasitemia was
twice as high in HIV-infected multigravidae as in HIV-negative multigravidae.
Malaria may also have an effect on HIV infections in nonpregnant adults.
Recently, a Malawian study has demonstrated that malaria-infected adults
have 7-fold higher HIV viral loads than malaria-free adults (1). Whether a
similar change in viral loads occurs in pregnant women (which could affect
mother-to-child transmission) remains to be seen.
1. Hoffman, I. F., Jere, C. S., Taylor, T. E., Munthali, P., Dyer, J. R.,
Wirima, J. J., Rogerson, S. J., Kumwenda, N., Eron, J. J., Fiscus, S. A.,
Chakraborty, H., Taha, T. E., Cohen, M. S. & Molyneux, M. E. (1999). The
effect of _Plasmodium falciparum_ malaria on HIV-1 RNA blood plasma
concentration. AIDS 13, 487-94.
2. Parise, M. E., Ayisi, J. G., Nahlen, B. L., Schultz, L. J., Roberts, J.
M., Misore, A., Muga, R., Oloo, A. J. & Steketee, R. W. (1998). Efficacy of
sulfadoxine-pyrimethamine for prevention of placental malaria in an area of
Kenya with a high prevalence of malaria and human immunodeficiency virus
infection. Am J Trop Med Hyg 59, 813-22.
3. Steketee, R. W., Wirima, J. J., Bloland, P. B., Chilima, B., Mermin, J.
H., Chitsulo, L. & Breman, J. G. (1996). Impairment of a pregnant woman's
acquired ability to limit _Plasmodium falciparum_ by infection with human
immunodeficiency virus type-1. Am J Trop Med Hyg 55, 42-9.
4. Verhoeff, F. H., Brabin, B. J., Hart, C. A., Chimsuku, L., Kazembe, P. &
Broadhead, R. L. (1999). Increased prevalence of malaria in HIV-infected
pregnant women and its implications for malaria control. Trop Med Int
Health 4, 5-12.
--
Steven Meshnick, M.D., Ph.D.
Professor of Epidemiology
