[The increase in HIV viral load in malaria infected patients is likely to
be important for the rapid spread of HIV in tropical Africa, and as
suggested it may increase the mother-to-child transmission. It is
surprising that HIV infection reduce parasitemia in primigravidae, and one
wonder if it is really a true finding with a biological background.
Placental malaria is seen more often in primigravidae compared to
multigravidae and it would be expected that HIV-infection had the strongest
impact on primigravidae. - Mod. EP
